notes:
James Hahn began the final round of the Wells Fargo Championship trailing Rickie Fowler by two strokes at 7-under 209. His final-round 2-under 70 against Fowler's 2-over 74 was enough to pit Hahn and Roberto Castro against each other in sudden death at 9-under 279. On the first extra hole, No. 18, Hahn's par proved good enough for his second career PGA TOUR win in his 97th PGA TOUR start at the age of 34 years, 6 months, 6 days. He previously won the 2015 Northern Trust Open, also via sudden death.   
   
 The 2016 Wells Fargo Championship marked the seventh playoff in event history and first since 2013, when Derek Ernst beat David Lynn on the first extra hole, No. 18.   
   
   Roberto Castro, who lost in sudden death to James Hahn, needed a win at the 2016 Wells Fargo Championship to move from the alternate list to the field of the following week's PLAYERS Championship.   
   
 With his T4 at the 2016 Wells Fargo Championship, Phil Mickelson extended his record of most top-10 finishes in the event to nine in 13 appearances; T5/2004, T7/2005, T3/2007, T5/2009, 2nd/2010, T9/2011, 3rd/2013, T4 in 2015 and T4/2016.   
   
 Defending champion and two-time Wells Fargo Championship winner(2010) Rory McIlroy rebounded from a 1-over 73 in round three with a 6-under 66 in the final round to finish at 7-under 281 and T4. Following a bogey at the first, McIlroy reeled off birdies at Nos. 4, 5, 7, 8, 10, 11, 14 and 16.   
   
   Roberto Castro and Carlos Ortiz became the fifth and sixth players, respectively, to record an eagle on the“Green Mile”(Nos. 16-18). Castro eagled the par-4 No. 18 in the second round, while Ortiz aced the par-3 17th in the third round.   
   
   Rory McIlroy has played 55 consecutive par-5s in the Wells Fargo Championship without a bogey. His last bogey on a par-5 at Quail Hollow came at No. 5 in round three of 2013. He played the par fives in 12-under par in 2016.   
   
   Rory McIlroy made his seventh start in the Wells Fargo Championship in 2016, where he has collected six top-10 finishes; 2010/Won, 2011/MC, 2012/T2, 2013/T10, 2014/T8, 2015/Won and 2016/T4.   
   
 Following an 11-over 83 in the third round, Jason Gore recorded a 7-under 65 in the final round. His 18-stroke improvement tied the tournament record for biggest swing between rounds with Brendon de Jonge, who followed an 8-over 80 in round one of 2014 with a 10-under 62 in round two. Gore finished T41.
